>2016
Political shift on the right away from anti-gay rhetoric in favor of greater focus on immigration and the economy. Trump says "LGBTQ" at Republican convention. Encountered a lot of especially younger people who expressed a feeling of optimism for a new paradigm in which these culture war issues might no longer dominate the political conversation. Trans issues are far down the list of hot button news items.
>2023
Culture wars are inescapable and no one can stop talking about trannies. RW memes have devolved into trannyjaks and spamming YWNBAW. The incel-to-trans pipeline idea balloons from a 4chan urban legend in 2017 to being publicly discussed on mainstream platforms. Harry Potter has gone from being employed in liberal and leftist rhetoric so frequently as to become a meme to being aggressively boycotted over trans issues. Trans girls in women's restrooms are treated like the most critical issue of the day and painted as monsters and creeps by mainstream conservative media.

What happened? I feel very sad about the way that public discourse has narrowed so radically in fewer than ten years. It's like this little window opened up and these weird possibilities of political heterodoxy emerged, and then just as rapidly, it slammed shut, and now everyone has "gender ideology" in their vocabulary and a culture war poison pill comes with every position. Political participation has become effectively unconscionable for me and it just seems like reasonable discourse on especially trans issues has just died a cruel death while simultaneously drowning out other issues. It's sad.

Trans people are a useful tool for conservatives to use to drum up support (although not actually as useful as they think). Trans people got a little gasp of positive press before the gamergate shit shit dropped. When I first came out in 2005-ish, cis people didn't know what the fuck we were. A few trans people made it into the mainstream in the early 10s and tried to positively represent us (Laverne Cox, for example), and the internet increasingly helped trans people, who are often disconnected from each other, to increasingly build community and share experiences and advice for surviving, transitioning, passing. As a result, more people were realizing they were trans and agitating for recognition and legal rights--then there was a massive kickback mostly started by very online people, around 2014-2016. Right-wing politicians, pundits, and influencers started picking up on and riffing on that when they were picking up on other far-right talking points and concepts.

Despite it working very well on some of their audience, it's actually not working as well as they would like, though. Most people might be put off by trans people and ignorant about how medical and social transition looks for a minor, but your average American doesn't actually HATE trans people or want them dead. My problem with this explanation is that very little about the new right in 2015/16 was concerned with trans people. The main instigating catalyst in Europe was an intersection of the failures of pluralism, European integration, and neocon bellicosity over the war in Syria, which collided all at once in 2015. Trump's signature issues were immigration and trade. The right's *successes* in this period were based precisely on issues unrelated to the culture wars. Since then, the right has stagnated, if anything, as conservatives and the far right alike lose their minds over bathrooms. I believe you're quite right to say that it's a losing fight; it's not only based on falsehoods but no more practicable in the long run than any other culture war battle that conservatives have lost in the past fifty years. But there is no reason to think that the right needed to fight this battle in the first place, or that it has been useful to them in the past ten years. My experience says the opposite.

>They don't need an excuse to want us dead, as not being cis is good enough, and nothing...will make them stop agitating for us to be repressed and killed.
It's not unique to your position, which appears to favor the left, but what I am most troubled by is the need across the political spectrum to portray enemies as particularly dishonest, murderous, or otherwise unreasonable, which gives us permission to be unreasonable and even violent in our reply. I've seen this happen to both the left and the right as polarization has deepened—I hear both accuse the other of violent hatred. Obviously there are political incentives to violence, dishonesty, and unreason, but it's a sign of a really broken polity that we're so eager to preclude reasonable discourse. Heterodoxy and even honest conversation become impossible when you are forced to take positions based on "what's good for me" vs. "who wants me killed" rather than what is true.

Of course—I don't mean to accuse you of harboring violent thoughts, and I'm not so naive to think that such people don't exist among the right. I guess the principal issue is that when we do adopt the position that an enemy is unreasonable, it actually becomes very hard to discern who is saying so out of necessity rather than out of malice.

There is a belief among political radicals right and left that mere discourse and dialectic can never regulate itself properly because of bad faith actors who will infiltrate and undermine it, and these people must be deplatformed and denied. For the left, this means something like people who secretly have hateful and genocidal plans, while for the right it's more like people seeking to justify their violence and criminality. There's some validity to this, but it has a corollary: just as the naivety of good faith dialogue can attract bad actors who use it as a cover, the cynicism of the radical is attractive to others because it offers a justification for their desire for violence and cruelty. And it's very difficult to tell the difference. I don't think it's the responsibility of you or I that more powerful people are poisoning the well, but I also feel a certain responsibility to maintain openness if I really believe in a politics that is reasonable and frank. Today it feels very hard to do that.

I've been thinking on this a lot. This article in specific is always in the back of my mind. A huge part has been the sidelining of medical transition. Compare the slogans at the time "trans healthcare is a human right" to more current stuff like "trans lives matter". Recently I've also been thinking a lot about Leelah Alcorn, and the outcry surrounding her abuse and suicide. Bills were drawn and the sitting president commented on her death and called for action. There seemed to be mobilization around the treatment of trans people, even for a brief time, and on a larger scale than anything we've seen before or since. Now a trans woman kills herself, including people in media positions and the like, and word barely even gets around the trans community.

you are stuck in a common situation that happens to young trans women that is not your fault, is not entirely in your control and you are being treated unfairly by both your family and society at large. all of this feels really bad and painful and I'm sorry you're going through such an awful experience, your pain is real and it matters.

it's going to be difficult but you need to realize your negative feelings are largely a reflection of your situation and if you do the right things to change it, which is totally feasible for you, you will be able to get out, meet people that like you, have new experiences, change your perspective, distance yourself from your past, and through all of this you will be able to have a happy and fulfilling life. you have decades of being a woman ahead of you, don't forget that.

practically you need to resort to some of the things trans girls do in oppressive situations like this. you need to build a support network of online trans friends, like in DMs or discord server where people understand the struggle. you should continue your relationship because getting a person that loves you will provide with the emotional support and potentially financial means you need to move away.
make an online presence like on twitter and cultivate some friendly simp audience, they could be willing to help you with money, and in longer term you could create a GoFundMe, explain your tragic situation and get a lot of sympathy and money from people.
Aside from this you should continue to pursue genuine life avenues like getting good grades to go to college, having an excuse to move out and getting a loan to do it. do not give up on your dreams due to the temporary set backs that seems so huge to you now but will become less so in the future as you mature.
On top of this all you could consider online sex work to get some extra money which might help.

Overall you should have hope. People in your situation have succeed. You can do it too sister

Goal of the thread: At the end of the day, try to write a journal entry listing positive experiences you had throughout the day, cute things you've seen, things that were nice, you get the idea.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

>>29539422
standard dose of pioglitazone is 30mg per day, not to exceed 45mg.
some trans girls do 15mg a day when cutting (to save money/wear and tear on the body) and 30mg a day when gaining. that's up to you.
you also ideally want to gain as fast as possible when in a gain cycle on pio since rapid gain makes your body prefer to make new fat cells (placed in feminine spots with proper female estrogen/testosterone level + the pio) instead of filling old ones (where your male fat cells already exist).
try to stick to healthy, good fats when you do this. trans fats lead directly to visceral fat (which is going to encourage male fat patterning if you're struggling with that). alcohol is bad for this too.
pioglitazone is still the wild west as far as the most effective doses/methods/timing goes for feminization, so ymmv, do your research, etc.
but the standard for virtually guaranteed results either way seems to be 30mg a day.

Evidence that rosiglitazone, a similar drug from the family of glitazones, improves subcutaneous fat deposition beyond lower body (including face)
source: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2895409/
It's likely that due to pio's similarity, it has the same effect.

Thread in a "women-only" sureddit about aesthetic self improvement, with anecdotal evidence that pioglitazone has improved their fat distribution:
>"Right, there's only 1 study about thiazolidinedione showing it can manipulate subcut fat, and it was done on a specific subpopulation (mtf trans) and in specific conditions (already had hrt, wanted to increase redistribution)
>but I given the other things I knew ab, I decided the parts we knew kinda fitted well enough together to be worth trying, so I've been playing with oral pioglitazone, and desu the result are nothing short of amazing."
>and the few ppl also using it (including 1 who just had preexisting diabetis then transitioned) reported results that are wayyy outside the normal. hopefully we'll have more research on that.
(this refers to that study we already know here)
>I had some facial fat loss maybe due to the various weird stuff I tried (not just tretinoin lol) + a very intense diet that left me with chicken wings, but at 6 month of pio I've regained everything in the face - and some more! and it's had a great effect on hips/butt which was my #1 failo before, even after a fat transfer..."
Again, this is anecdotal evidence that pio has at redistribution effects beyond the usually-studied abdominal and femoral VAT and SAT, including the face subcutaneous fat. Subject is a trans woman that reports not having had androgens for 6 years.
source: https://www.reddit.com/r/Vindicta/comments/txxv5x/comment/i3rrt1q/?utm_source=reddit&utm_medium=web2x&context=3

Not pio-related but here is anecdotal evidence that E2 gel improved facial distribution on a 35 year old PCOS woman
>"Estrogen has done for my face what no peels, fillers, treatments were ever able to do. I have spent thousands of dollars on skin care like laprairie and it doesn’t compare. Estrogen has thickened my skin and restores volume in my cheeks. My under eye has filled up. My lips too ( ok not like fillers but they stay hydrated and look better). The tone is the most important change. It just looks fresh and plump and rosier.
source: https://old.reddit.com/r/estrogel/comments/tpzz97/review_of_topical_estrogens_for_facial_effects/i3ovhs1/

Rosiglitazone has a lipogenic effect on facial subcutaneous depots.
>"Subcutaneous preadipocytes were isolated from human facial and abdominal skin and cultured in the presence of differentiation factors including rosiglitazone [...] Unexpected superior adipogenic capacity of facial preadipocytes was observed; more facial preadipocytes differentiated in response to rosiglitazone than abdominal preadipocytes and facial preadipocytes retained their ability to differentiate"
source: https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.4161/21623945.2014.955402

However, glitazones, as ligands of the PPARgamma receptors, may have a negative impact on breast growth. Some studies report breast cancer growth inhibition when glitazones like pioglitazone and rosiglitazone are used and activate PPARgamma:
>"Ligands for PPARγ include natural compounds such as fatty acids and their derivatives and synthetic agents such as the antidiabetic drugs rosiglitazone (Avandia) and pioglitazone (Actos) [13]. Although central role of PPAR-γ has been demonstrated in the differentiation of adipose cells, PPARγ has also been shown to regulate the growth, differentiation, and gene expression in number of different cancer cells"
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2676298/

Example would be

>reasonably consistent diet and exercise throughout (whether that's shit diet and no exercise or healthy and exercise, doesn't matter but noting what it was is good info)
>start at weight x, take extensive measurements
>change weight by y over time period t, take extensive measurements
>return to weight x over time period u, take extensive measurements
>introduce pioglitazone dose
>change weight by y in over time period t, take extensive measurements
>compare measurements and note changes between hrt plus weight change (incl. y = 0 if chosen) alone vs hrt plus weight change plus pioglitazone

>prog but only sometimes
Some people do on/off to mimic the menstrual cycle and give TEBs (terminal end buds) a chance to propagate and proliferate. Those structures are responsible for the outgrowth of the primary mammary (breast) structure. Some people suggest either staying on it 24/7 or not at all (i.e. Lena) due to the fact that:
>Alveoli (milk sacs) induced by Progesterone will undergo apoptosis (cell death) after cessation of Prog (happens in cis women, breast prepares for pregnancy, then returns to senescent (dormant) state when no longer needed)
>This process of differentiation/apoptosis increases risk of breast cancer
Progesterone isn't needed for side branching necessarily (the action of secondary branches appearing in the breast structure, that is, secondary to the TEB formed branches), but it does seem to help massively. Your choice here, personally I stay on it 24/7 because I like the volume increase and mood/sleep benefits, although I might try cycling.
>pio maybe something

This is probs referring to Bicalutamide but applies to most Anti Androgens or any other oral drug who's primary metabolic pathway is through the liver. At MtF doses of Bica the incidence rate is fairly low. The way to keep an eye out is monitoring Liver Enzymes with a blood test.
>if you take too much you cuck yourself
Don't go over 6-700 pg/mL troughs and you'll probs be fine, best to aim for the lowest dose possible for meaningful effects, push higher from there if you feel like it. Zero in on the best level for you.

Depends on if you're doing monotherapy or not. With an AA, you're probs okay dipping all the way down to a min of 80 pg/mL. Mono no less than 200 pg/mL. Again, everyone is different, zero in on the best level for you.

>More specifically, studies in cisgender men and transfeminine people have found that estradiol levels of around 200 pg/mL (734 pmol/L) generally suppress testosterone levels by about 90% (to ~50 ng/dL [1.7 nmol/L]), while estradiol levels of around 500 pg/mL (1,840 pmol/L) suppress testosterone levels by about 95% on average (to ~20–30 ng/dL [0.7–1.0 nmol/L]) (Wiki; Graphs).

There doesn't seem to be any concrete evidence pointing towards premature stunting of breast growth by starting Progesterone 'too early' Up to you here again, might be worth putting off, it can cause some paradoxical effects (masculinization, in this case) in some people, will complicate things further, especially if you're just starting out, might be confusing and hard to wrestle with.
>And you're on it 24/7 but if I wanted to cycle would once a week each month be enough of a cycle given you said immitating menstrual cycles
You'd wanna cycle it bi-weekly, picrel is the ovarian cycle. It's around 4 weeks long, and Progesterone spikes at week 2 and stays elevated for two weeks. So you'd do 2 weeks on Progesterone, 2 weeks off Progesterone.
>someone was boofing 200mg idk how often that was
>so how do you take it and 24/7 is the start of a week for 200mg, or a lower amount daily??
You'd need to take it daily, it has a really short half life. Take it at night, as a suppository (rectally) if you do. It has really poor bioavailability if you take it orally, rectal is much better.
